s identify neglected resources for political judgment in today's conditions of pluralism and interdependency.Three assumptions inform these essays: the many dimensions of prudence cannot be adequately represented in the lexicon of any single discipline; the Aristotelian focus on prudence as rational calculation needs to be balanced by the Ciceronian emphasis on prudence as discursive performance embedded in familiar social practices; and understanding prudence requires attention to how it operates through the communicative media and public discourses that constitute the political community. Contributors, besides the editor, are Stephen H. Browne, Robert W. Cape Jr., Maurice Charland, Peter J. Diamond, Eugene Garver, James Jasinski, John S. Nelson, and Christine L. Oravec.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aPrudence. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh  aAristotelian.  aBrowne.  aChristine L. Oravec.  aCiceronian.  aEugene Garver.  aJaames Jasinski.  aJohn S. Nelson.  aLanguage.  aLinguistics.  aMaurice Charland.  aPeter J. Diamond.  aPhilosophy.  aPolitical.  aRhetoric.  aRobert Hariman.  aRobert W. Cape Jr.  aStephen H.  aTheory.1 aBrowne, Stephen H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCape, Robert W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCharland, Maurice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiamond, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarver, Eugene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHariman, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHariman, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJasinski, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.